    "Evaluation": {
      "text": "Typical work up for abdominal pain\nUpright\nchest x-ray\nand\nabdominal series\nto assess for free air\nCan identify large distended stomach on x-ray\nCT imaging if safe and indicated",
      "subsections": {},
      "tables": [],
      "links": []
    },
    "Management": {
      "text": "Nasogastric\nor orogastric decompression is first line therapy\nTypically a large special tube required which is placed under anesthesiologist supervision in OR\nResuscitation with fluids and intravenous antibiotics as indicated\nIf conservative measures fail or gastric infarction suspected, surgical intervention mandatory",
      "subsections": {},
      "tables": [],
      "links": []
    },
    "Disposition": {
      "text": "Patient may require emergent surgical decompression\nIf improvement with non-operative decompression, may require admission for continued monitoring",
      "subsections": {},
      "tables": [],
      "links": []
    },
    "Complications": {
      "text": "Bowel necrosis\nwith or without perforation\nAbdominal compartment syndrome\nSepsis\n/\nSeptic shock\nIf gastric necrosis and/or perforation not recognized and treatment delayed, mortality reaches 80%",
      "subsections": {},
      "tables": [],
      "links": []
    },
